and there's a whole
bunch of mechanisms

00:43:27.720 --> 00:43:30.222
that help that process.

00:43:30.222 --> 00:43:31.680
That sort of
governance seems to be

00:43:31.680 --> 00:43:35.220
important to allow stories to
get better and to be explored.

00:43:35.220 --> 00:43:39.330
Where are some other
places in which governance

00:43:39.330 --> 00:43:42.409
exists that you admire and
respect of that nature,

00:43:42.409 --> 00:43:44.700
whether it's in the pursuit
of better stories or better

00:43:44.700 --> 00:43:45.540
institutions?

00:43:50.722 --> 00:43:52.680
ANTOINE BELLO: First, a
side note on Wikipedia.

00:43:52.680 --> 00:43:56.580
The governance is much
lighter than you think.

00:43:56.580 --> 00:43:58.980
For instance, the credibility
of the person who writes

00:43:58.980 --> 00:44:01.260
is never taken into
account, and you

00:44:01.260 --> 00:44:03.870
would think, oh my god,
that's how you end up

00:44:03.870 --> 00:44:05.700
having so poor pages.

00:44:05.700 --> 00:44:07.000
But that's quite the opposite.

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:10.710
People who don't feel empowered
to write about the subject

00:44:10.710 --> 00:44:12.781
simply don't.

00:44:12.781 --> 00:44:14.280
And I can tell you
on the other end,

00:44:14.280 --> 00:44:17.040
I've tried to rectify
something on my Wikipedia page.

00:44:17.040 --> 00:44:19.620
I was banned from it.

00:44:19.620 --> 00:44:21.600
You would think
that you know best.

00:44:21.600 --> 00:44:24.660
No, you don't.

00:44:24.660 --> 00:44:27.690
Because maybe, Mr. Bello, you
have a problem with the truth.

00:44:27.690 --> 00:44:36.120
Maybe your memories
were a story as well.

00:44:36.120 --> 00:44:41.430
So I'm not sure I really
see that type of governance

00:44:41.430 --> 00:44:45.030
anywhere else or I
admire it anywhere else.

00:44:45.030 --> 00:44:48.150
What I see is that large
companies like yours

00:44:48.150 --> 00:44:53.190
are trying, at the moment, to
get to something like that.

00:44:53.190 --> 00:44:56.580
Facebook is trying very hard
with their tens of thousands

00:44:56.580 --> 00:44:59.880
of fact checkers.

00:44:59.880 --> 00:45:06.312
And Google, you have a
lot of processes in place,

00:45:06.312 --> 00:45:16.290
the right to be forgotten
and you can report bad pages

00:45:16.290 --> 00:45:22.800
or you can report every time you
suspect a scam or an operation

00:45:22.800 --> 00:45:27.840
to increase the search
engine ranking of a page.

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:29.730
You can alert Google to it.

00:45:29.730 --> 00:45:31.770
I think that's pretty powerful.

00:45:31.770 --> 00:45:34.080
It's only the beginning, though.

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:38.280
And your company, probably,
among all the others,

00:45:38.280 --> 00:45:41.400
probably has the
biggest responsibility.

00:45:41.400 --> 00:45:44.190
If I remind correctly,
the goal of Google

00:45:44.190 --> 00:45:49.330
was to organize all the
information around the world.

00:45:49.330 --> 00:45:49.830
Wow.

00:45:49.830 --> 00:45:51.300
That's a tall order.

00:45:51.300 --> 00:45:54.302
You'd better get it
right for our sake.

00:45:54.302 --> 00:45:55.510
AUDIENCE: It's not just that.

00:45:55.510 --> 00:45:59.420
It's also to make it universally
useful and accessible,

00:45:59.420 --> 00:46:01.670
and that question of universally
useful and accessible

00:46:01.670 --> 00:46:05.310
is obviously a question which
involves multiple perspectives.

00:46:05.310 --> 00:46:07.920
ANTOINE BELLO: Yes,
exactly, and I'm not--

00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:11.220
for instance, there is
this debate right now

00:46:11.220 --> 00:46:14.490
about should Google go back
to China, for instance,

00:46:14.490 --> 00:46:17.790
and tailor the search
engine to the needs

00:46:17.790 --> 00:46:20.790
of the Chinese government.

00:46:20.790 --> 00:46:24.540
I follow this debate and
I find it fascinating,

00:46:24.540 --> 00:46:27.330
to be honest, because I don't
have the answer to that.

00:46:27.330 --> 00:46:29.940
There is a part of me who
says, no, of course no.

00:46:29.940 --> 00:46:31.500
Don't go to China.

00:46:31.500 --> 00:46:32.610
They banned Wikipedia.

00:46:32.610 --> 00:46:38.400
Why would Google go and get in
bed with the Chinese leaders?

00:46:38.400 --> 00:46:44.150
And at the same time
I have to think,

00:46:44.150 --> 00:46:48.030
a search engine that would
do 99% of what Google does

00:46:48.030 --> 00:46:50.190
in the rest of
the world would be

00:46:50.190 --> 00:46:51.990
a nice service to
the Chinese people

00:46:51.990 --> 00:46:55.945
and would accommodate,
like you said,

00:46:55.945 --> 00:46:58.800
their vision of the world
which is not the same as ours,

00:46:58.800 --> 00:47:03.000
and ours is not better.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:07.920
So it's typically the type of
subjects where I am divided

00:47:07.920 --> 00:47:12.300
and I refrain from
the temptation

00:47:12.300 --> 00:47:13.290
of judging too quickly.

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:17.640
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:17.640 --> 00:47:19.297
AUDIENCE: Two more
questions, please.

00:47:19.297 --> 00:47:20.380
ANTOINE BELLO: Over there.

00:47:27.565 --> 00:47:29.490
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:47:29.490 --> 00:47:32.890
I'm curious in the idea
of bringing this consensus

00:47:32.890 --> 00:47:37.240
to the political area
to explain my point

00:47:37.240 --> 00:47:39.760
and to ask your opinion.

00:47:39.760 --> 00:47:43.130
Some democracies that try
democracy by consensus,

00:47:43.130 --> 00:47:45.250
it brought some
weaknesses to them

00:47:45.250 --> 00:47:48.310
because it takes time and
effort and it's easier

00:47:48.310 --> 00:47:52.410
to be quick and not
make the efforts.

00:47:52.410 --> 00:47:54.787
Do you have an opinion
on that or do you--

00:47:54.787 --> 00:47:55.870
ANTOINE BELLO: Not really.

00:47:55.870 --> 00:47:58.480
It would be a stretch to say
that I have an opinion on that.

00:47:58.480 --> 00:48:00.070
I lived in Japan for a while.

00:48:00.070 --> 00:48:02.830
I lived in Japan for a
year and a half in the '90s

00:48:02.830 --> 00:48:09.550
and I was extremely impressed
by their governing by consensus.

00:48:09.550 --> 00:48:11.320
It was extremely
impressive, the way

00:48:11.320 --> 00:48:16.630
they were able to raise the
age of retirement at the time

00:48:16.630 --> 00:48:21.740
without any dissent, without
anybody taking to the streets.

00:48:21.740 --> 00:48:26.410
It was a lesson to me
in reason and democracy.

00:48:26.410 --> 00:48:28.690
At the same time,
I know it comes

00:48:28.690 --> 00:48:31.930
with plenty of inconvenience.

00:48:31.930 --> 00:48:35.620
Like you said, the democratic
process in Japan is slow.

00:48:35.620 --> 00:48:37.780
Political parties
and politicians

00:48:37.780 --> 00:48:43.900
are corrupted and can be easily
bought, from what I hear.

00:48:43.900 --> 00:48:46.440
So I won't make it an example.

00:48:46.440 --> 00:48:49.590
But no, I don't have a
firm opinion on that.

00:48:52.960 --> 00:48:53.960
AUDIENCE: Last question.

00:48:53.960 --> 00:48:55.126
AUDIENCE: One last question.

00:48:59.914 --> 00:49:00.455
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:49:00.455 --> 00:49:02.880
Thank you for the talk.

00:49:02.880 --> 00:49:06.140
I was curious what's your view
on artificial intelligence

00:49:06.140 --> 00:49:09.770
and the evolution of
that technology based

00:49:09.770 --> 00:49:13.706
on the fact that more and more
we'll be using data provided

00:49:13.706 --> 00:49:16.970
by, or information provided by
machines, as the truth somehow.

00:49:16.970 --> 00:49:19.490
ANTOINE BELLO: I'm so interested
by artificial intelligence

00:49:19.490 --> 00:49:21.680
that I wrote a whole
novel about it.

00:49:21.680 --> 00:49:24.421
It's called "Ada,"
A-D-A. It's the name

00:49:24.421 --> 00:49:26.670
of an artificial intelligence
developed in the Silicon

00:49:26.670 --> 00:49:29.900
Valley, not far
from Mountain View.

00:49:29.900 --> 00:49:31.400
In Mountain View,
actually, I think.

00:49:31.400 --> 00:49:34.070
No, in Stanford.

00:49:34.070 --> 00:49:36.450
And that gets stolen.

00:49:36.450 --> 00:49:40.850
And the program gets stolen,
disappears from the hard drive,

00:49:40.850 --> 00:49:45.260
and the question is, now we have
this program out in the open,

00:49:45.260 --> 00:49:47.420
what will anyone do with it?

00:49:47.420 --> 00:49:48.625
What will it do with itself?

00:49:51.290 --> 00:49:54.950
My role as a writer is
not to provide answers.

00:49:54.950 --> 00:49:58.260
I think it's to ask the
questions in an elegant manner.

00:49:58.260 --> 00:50:03.770
So I think that's what I
tried to do in "Ada," explore

00:50:03.770 --> 00:50:08.310
all the possibilities offered
by artificial intelligence.

00:50:08.310 --> 00:50:10.100
And there are
many, but of course

00:50:10.100 --> 00:50:16.620
reminding the reader of all
the risks that go with it.

00:50:16.620 --> 00:50:20.180
And there is no real conclusion
at the end of the book.

00:50:20.180 --> 00:50:22.010
I think any
conclusion would have

00:50:22.010 --> 00:50:30.125
been a usurpation of my powers
and privileges as a writer.

00:50:30.125 --> 00:50:30.958
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:50:34.820 --> 00:50:36.530
AUDIENCE: Thank you, everyone.

00:50:36.530 --> 00:50:37.990
So I think it's the end.

00:50:37.990 --> 00:50:38.740
ANTOINE BELLO: OK.

00:50:38.740 --> 00:50:40.695
AUDIENCE: Thank you
very much, Antoine.

00:50:40.695 --> 00:50:41.570
ANTOINE BELLO: Merci.

00:50:41.570 --> 00:50:45.520
[APPLAUSE]

